statement:
Prove, directly from the $\epsilon$-definition of the limit of a
sequence, that

\begin{align*}\lim_{n \to \infty} \left( -\frac{2}{3} \right)^n = 0\end{align*}

hints:
A sequence ${a_n}$ converges to a number \emph{L} if for any
$\epsilon>0$ there exists a number $N_\epsilon$ such that

\begin{align*}\text{if } n \geq N_\epsilon \quad\text{then}\quad |a_n - L| < \epsilon\end{align*}
